&gt; Paul,
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s great. I&#39;ve seen some slick stuff done with Theories in
&gt; Groovy. What is the error message if a line like this fails?
&gt;
&gt; assert languages[&#39;tom&#39;] == [&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;]
&gt;
&gt; Do you get an informative message? Thanks,
&gt;

Out of the box (i.e. using the assertion as above) you get the following 
error message:

java.lang.AssertionError: Expression: (languages[tom] == [Java, 
Groovy]). Values: languages = {tom=[JavaScript, Groovy],
 dick=[C#, Ruby]}

This is informative but probably not as pretty as possible. Using 
assertThat from the same example (i.e. assertThat languages[&#39;tom&#39;], 
is([&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;])) yields:

java.lang.AssertionError:
Expected: is &lt;[Java, Groovy]&gt;
     got: &lt;[JavaScript, Groovy]&gt;

So, a friendlier error message bug arguably a less friendly expression 
of the test.

You can always use JUnit&#39;s assertEquals by statically importing 
assertEquals (i.e. test becomes assertEquals languages[&#39;tom&#39;], [&quot;Java&quot;, 
&quot;Groovy&quot;]), you get:

java.lang.AssertionError: expected:&lt;[JavaScript, Groovy]&gt; but 
was:&lt;[Java, Groovy]&gt;

And of course you can roll your own error message at anytime with the 
normal assert, i.e. this test:

        assert languages[&#39;tom&#39;] == [&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;], &#92;
            &quot;&#92;n Expected: ${[&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;]}&#92;nbut found: 
${languages[&#39;tom&#39;]}&quot;

produces this result:

java.lang.AssertionError:
 Expected: [&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;]
but found: [&quot;JavaScript&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;].

Though you would probably refactor out &#39;actual&#39; and &#39;expected&#39; as 
variables in this case, i.e. perhaps something like this:

def actual = languages[&#39;tom&#39;]
def expected = [&quot;Java&quot;, &quot;Groovy&quot;]
assert actual == expected, &quot;&quot;&quot;
 Expected: $expected
but found: $actual&quot;&quot;&quot;


Cheers, Paul.

